Answer: It looks like you are trying to find $P(\overline{B} \cap A)$. This can be done with Baye's Theorem:
\begin{equation}
P(A \cap \overline{B}) = \frac{P(A \cap \overline{B})}{P(\overline{B})}.
\end{equation}
Hence:
\begin{equation}
P(\overline{B}) = 1 - P(B) = 0.5
\end{equation}
and
\begin{equation}
P(A \cap \overline{B}) = P(A) = 0.2
\end{equation}
So:
\begin{equation}
0.2 = \frac{P(A \cap \overline{B})}{P(\overline{B})}
\end{equation}
and
\begin{equation}
P(A \cap \overline{B}) = 0.2 \frac{1}{0.5} = 0.4
\end{equation}
Then:
\begin{equation}
P(\overline{B} \cap A) = 1 - P(\overline{B \cup A}) = 1 - (0.2 + 0.5 - 0.4) = 1 - 0.3 = 0.7.
\end{equation}

